            <h2>Negations Overview</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">N</span>negations in Old English are straightforward, but there are 
            a few things that set them apart from negations in modern English.
            </p>
            <h3>Word Order</h3>
            <p>The negative particle always precedes the verb, and auixlliary verbs like 'do' are not generally used in negative
                constructions, as they are in the English 'I do not like', 'I cannot come'. Negations often start a sentence or 
                clause, so we often see constructions such as '<em>Ne com heo</em>' - '<em>She didn't come</em>' (literally 
                '<em>not come she</em> or '<em>Ne stel Ã°u</em>' - '<em>Do not steal!</em>' (literally '<em>no steal you!</em>').
                </p>
        
            <h3>Negated Verbs</h3>
            <p>Sometimes the negative particle that precedes the verb ('<em>ne</em>' in the examples above) is joined to the start
                of the verb. This phenomenon only happens with certain verbs, the most important being '<em>wesan</em>' - '<em>to be</em>',
                '<em>habban</em>' - '<em>to have</em>', and '<em>willan</em>' - '<em>to wish/want</em>'. When this fusing of the negative 
                particle to the start of the verb happens, sometimes the initial letters of the verb or the vowel in '<em>ne</em>' is lost,
                leaving forms such as '<em>nis</em>' (a contraction of '<em>ne is</em>' - '<em>is not</em>') or '<em>noldon</em>'
                (a contraction of '<em>ne woldon</em>' - '<em>did not want</em>'). This process also happens with certain adverbs and adjectives
                which give us forms such as '<em>nan</em>' - '<em>none</em>(from '<em>ne an</em>' - '<em>not one</em>').
                    </p>
            <h3>Double Negatives</h3>
            <p>In modern English, negatives cancel each other out - so 'I don't not love Old English' means that you, in fact, <em>do</em> love
                it. In Old English, double negation simply emphasises the negation, and it is common to find negation applied to every
                word that can be made negative in a single sentence.
                        </p>
            
